Source_LV3_1_103f_cal.llb|(i32) line mask: determines which lines this VI reads. If you set line mask to -1 (all ones), the VI reads the entire port. If you set only bit n in line mask, the VI reads only line n of the port. If the state of line n is high, the VI sets bit n of pattern. The VI sets to 0 the bits of pattern that correspond to lines the VI has not read. The default setting for line mask is -1 which is shown as all ones since the binary representation is the default selection.62(u32) pattern: the data the VI read from the port.51(u32) task ID out: has the same value as task ID.

If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV3_1_103f_cal.llb|XON/XOFF is a software handshaking protocol you can use to avoid overflowing serial port buffers. When the receive buffer is nearly full, the receiver sends XOFF (<controlS> [decimal 19]) to tell the other device to stop sending data. When the receive buffer is sufficiently empty, the receiver sends XON (<controlQ> [decimal 17]) to indicate that transmission can begin again. When you enable XON/XOFF, the devices always interpret <controlQ> and <controlS> as XON and XOFF characters, never as data. When you disable XON/XOFF, you can send <controlQ> and <controlS> as data. Do not use XON/XOFF with binary data transfers because <controlQ> or <controlS> may be embedded in the data, and the devices will interpret them as XON and XOFF instead of data.

Source_LV3_1_103f_cal.llb|error in is a cluster of three elements (error?, code, and source) that describe the upstream error state, that is, the existance of any error preceeding the execution of the VI.  The VI executes normally only if no incoming error exists; otherwise it merely passes the error in value to error out.  error? is TRUE if an error occurred; the default value is FALSE.  code is the error code; the default value is 0.  source is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error; the default value is an empty string.

Source_LV3_1_103f_cal.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV3_1_MAINB_II.LLB|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV3_1_MAINB_II.LLB||error in is a cluster that describes the error status before this VI executes. If error in indicates that an error occurred before this VI was called, this VI may choose not to execute its function, but just pass the error through to its error out cluster. If no error has occurred, then this VI executes normally and sets its own error status in error out. Use the error handler VIs to look up the error code and to display the corresponding error message. Using error in and error out clusters is a convenient way to check errors and to specify execution order by wiring the error output from one subVI to the error input of the next.

If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV3_1_PWRTEST.LLB|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV5_1_103f_cal.llb|XON/XOFF is a software handshaking protocol you can use to avoid overflowing serial port buffers. When the receive buffer is nearly full, the receiver sends XOFF (<controlS> [decimal 19]) to tell the other device to stop sending data. When the receive buffer is sufficiently empty, the receiver sends XON (<controlQ> [decimal 17]) to indicate that transmission can begin again. When you enable XON/XOFF, the devices always interpret <controlQ> and <controlS> as XON and XOFF characters, never as data. When you disable XON/XOFF, you can send <controlQ> and <controlS> as data. Do not use XON/XOFF with binary data transfers because <controlQ> or <controlS> may be embedded in the data, and the devices will interpret them as XON and XOFF instead of data.

The VI executes normally only if no incoming error exists; otherwise it merely passes the error in value to error out.  error? is TRUE if an error occurred; the default value is FALSE.  code is the error code; the default value is 0.  source is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error; the default value is an empty string.

Source_LV5_1_103f_cal.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV5_1_Mainb_ii.llb|Normal Use:  When using subVIs that incorporate the error in/error out (or error I/O) structure, place this handler where you want to inform the user of an error, typically at the end of the I/O data path, as the last action of the program.  If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV5_1_Mainb_ii.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

If you set line mask to -1, the VI writes to the entire port and sets all the lines in the port to the states specified by the bits in pattern. If you set only bit n in line mask, the VI changes only line n in the port to the state that bit n of pattern specifies. The default setting for line mask is -1.51(u32) task ID out: has the same value as task ID.

Source_LV5_1_Mainb_ii.llb||error in is a cluster that describes the error status before this VI executes. If error in indicates that an error occurred before this VI was called, this VI may choose not to execute its function, but just pass the error through to its error out cluster. If no error has occurred, then this VI executes normally and sets its own error status in error out. Use the error handler VIs to look up the error code and to display the corresponding error message. Using error in and error out clusters is a convenient way to check errors and to specify execution order by wiring the error output from one subVI to the error input of the next.

If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV5_1_Pwrtest.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV6_103f_cal.llb|Normal Use:  When using subVIs that incorporate the error in/error out (or error I/O) structure, place this handler where you want to inform the user of an error, typically at the end of the I/O data path, as the last action of the program.  If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source. Source_LV6_103f_cal.llb|XON/XOFF is a software handshaking protocol you can use to avoid overflowing serial port buffers. When the receive buffer is nearly full, the receiver sends XOFF (<controlS> [decimal 19]) to tell the other device to stop sending data. When the receive buffer is sufficiently empty, the receiver sends XON (<controlQ> [decimal 17]) to indicate that transmission can begin again. When you enable XON/XOFF, the devices always interpret <controlQ> and <controlS> as XON and XOFF characters, never as data. When you disable XON/XOFF, you can send <controlQ> and <controlS> as data. Do not use XON/XOFF with binary data transfers because <controlQ> or <controlS> may be embedded in the data, and the devices will interpret them as XON and XOFF instead of data.

This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV6_Mainb_ii.llb|Normal Use:  When using subVIs that incorporate the error in/error out (or error I/O) structure, place this handler where you want to inform the user of an error, typically at the end of the I/O data path, as the last action of the program.  If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV6_Mainb_ii.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_LV6_Pwrtest.llb|Normal Use:  When using subVIs that incorporate the error in/error out (or error I/O) structure, place this handler where you want to inform the user of an error, typically at the end of the I/O data path, as the last action of the program.  If the error in status is ERROR, the handler creates a message describing the error and its source.  If the type of dialog = 1 (default), the message is displayed to the user, who can only acknowedge it.  If the type = 2, the user can acknowledge the message or abort execution; aborting a program with active I/O is not recommended.  If the type = 0, no message is displayed; this is used to process the error programmatically, and the error out cluster elements are wired to individual terminals for that reason.

Source_LV6_Pwrtest.llb|exception handling.  This mechanism is available either to set the error out status FALSE on what is normally an error or to set the status TRUE on what is normally not an error.  If exception action > 0, the error in code and source are checked.  If they match the exception code and source, the error out status is adjusted accordingly.  That is, if the action = 1, the error out status is set to FALSE and code is set to zero and if the action = 2, the error out is set to TRUE and the code is unchanged.  An empty exception source matches any error in source.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|advisory dialog? Set TRUE (default) if you want a dialog if function=0 and the file does not exist, or if function=2 or 3 and the file exists.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|append to file?  Set to TRUE if you want to append the data to a existing file; you can also set it TRUE to write to a new file.  Set to FALSE (default value) if you want to write the data to a new file or to replace an existing file.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|at the current file mark plus pos offset.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|at the current file mark plus pos offset.  This is the default value.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|close when?  Set TRUE (default) when you want to close the file when this VI is called.  Set to FALSE when you want to close the file only if this VI encounters an incoming error.  This input is useful when you use this VI inside a loop and want to close the file only on the last loop iteration or on an upstream error.  In that case, set close when? TRUE on the last iteration, and terminate the loop on the last iteration or when this VI returns an error.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|creates a new file or replaces a file if it exists and you give permission. Replacement is done by opening the file and setting EOF to 0. Error 43 occurs if the user elects to disallow the replacement using dialog.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|default name is the initial file name that appears in the selection box of the file dialog.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|error in is a cluster of three elements (error?, code, and source) that describe the upstream error state, that is, the existance of any error preceeding the execution of the VI.  The VI executes normally only if no incoming error exists; otherwise it merely passes the error in value to error out.  error? is TRUE if an error occurred; the default value is FALSE.  code is the error code; the default value is 0.  source is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error; the default value is an empty string.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|file path is the path name of the file.  If file path is empty (default value) or is Not A Path, the VI displays a File dialog box from which you can select a file.  Error 43 occurs if the user cancels the dialog.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|file path is the path name of the file. If file path is empty (default value) or is Not A Path, the VI displays a File dialog box from which you can select a file. Error 43 occurs if the user cancels the dialog.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|irefnum is the reference number of the open file. The value is Not A Refnum if the file cannot be opened.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|kReturns in byte count the number of bytes in the input buffer of the serial port indicated in port number.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|line mode  Set TRUE to read until a line marker or end of line is encounter or count characters are read.  Set FALSE (default value) to read until count characters are read or end of line is encountered.  A line mark is a carriage return, a line feed, or a carriage return followed by a line feed.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|lprompt is the message that appears below the list of files and directories (or folders) in the file dialog.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|new file path is the path of the file from which the VI read data.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|new file path is the path of the file opened or created.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open or create using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|new file path is the path of the file opened or created. You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open or create using dialog. new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|new file path is the path of the file opened.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|new file path is the path of the file to which the VI wrote data.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|number of lines is the maximum number of lines the VI reads.  The default value is -1 line, which means to read the entire file.  For this VI, a line is a character string ending with a carriage return, line feed, or a carriage return followed by a line feed; a string ending at the EOF; or a string that has the maximum line length specified by the max characters per line input.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|opens an existing file or creates a new file if one does not exist.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|opens an existing file. Error 7 occurs if the file cannot be found.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|pos offset specifies in characters how far from the location specified by pos mode that the operation begins.  The default value is 0.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|prompt is the message that appears below the list of files and directories in the file dialog.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|qReads the number of characters specified by requested byte count from the serial port indicated in port number.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|refnum is the reference number of the open file.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|refnum is the reference number of the open file.  The value is Not A Refnum if the file cannot be opened.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|rrsFile Dialog cancelled; set error out code to Cancelled By User; set refnum to NotaRefnum and file path to NotAPath.
Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|start of read offset is the position in the file, measured in characters (or bytes), at which the VI begins reading.

Source_lv8_103f_cal.llb|status is a Boolean array in which each bit describes a state of the GPIB Controller. If an error occurs, the GPIB VIs set bit 15. GPIB error is valid only if bit 15 of status is set.
